Ok based on what @dop251 found it appears that the issue is that Atomic operations require 64-bit alignment on 32-bit architectures.  

I _think_ the culprit is that the `fastclock` has a `time.Time` before using `atomicTime`. Since `time.Time` ends with a pointer (which would only be 32 bits for x86) we'll get off our alignment.  To fix this I _think_ we can just add a spacer to the `fastclock` struct (in fastclock.go): 
```golang
type fastclock struct {
	// current and clockEnd can be read via atomic loads.
	// Reads and writes of other fields require mu to be held.
	mu sync.Mutex

	start time.Time // Time corresponding to fasttime(0)
	//spacer for x86 arch
	_        int
	current  atomicTime // Current time (approximate)
	clockEnd atomicTime // When clock updater is supposed to stop (>= any existing deadline)
	running  bool       // Is a clock updater running?
}
```

